"n. 涩，酸，刻薄 无 无 无 acerbity (n.)  1570s, from Middle French acerbité, from Latin acerbitatem (nominative acerbitas) ""harshness, sharpness, bitterness,"" from acerbus ""bitter to taste, sharp, sour, tart"" (related to acer ""sharp;"" compare Latin superbus ""haughty,"" from super ""above""), from Proto-Italic *akro-po- ""sharp,"" from PIE *ak- ""sharp"" (see acrid). Earliest use in English is figurative, of ""sharp and bitter"" persons. Of tastes, from 1610s."
